The Fiat G. 12 was a three-engined Italian Transport and passenger aircraft. It could sit for 14 passengers in single or 24 paratroopers are transported on one of the benches. A total of 104 aircraft were built in the years 1940 to 1949.
GeschichteDas, and has been developed since the beginning of 1939 on the basis of experience with the Fiat G. 18, and represented a significant leap in development with a higher speed, range and altitude. The first flight of the prototype (I-ALIA) was held on 14. October, 1940. As the first series-21 passenger aircraft for the Aviolinee and the Ala Littoria were launched. Since Italy had in the meantime entered the war, supplied the first planes from June 1941, the Regia Aeronautica.
Military VerwendungAls first squadron was equipped with the 601° Squadriglia of the Servizi Aerei Speziali (SAS) of the G. 12, to be followed by the 606° Squadriglia. In the case of the supply of the bridgehead in Tunisia, a larger number G. 12 were lost.After the first series had been delivered, granted by the Italian air Ministry a contract on a further 100 aircraft of the transport version. Until the Italian armistice on 8. September 1943 were supplied a total of 52 aircraft. On 1. August 1943 were 28 aircraft available: 5 in the Aviolinee, 18 in the 601° and 606° Squadriglia and 5 in the Overhaul at Fiat in Turin. Two of these aircraft (W. no. 40 and 47), flew to the end of the war, the Aeronautica Cobelligerante Italiana on the allied side. Three aircraft of the Aviolinee (W. no. 7, 9, 13) were seized by the German Lufthansa in January 1944 and in February and April 1944 to the air force (transport season 4).Position of the aircraft of the Italian air transport companies, Deutsche Lufthansa Aktiengesellschaft, 28. November 1944, in: Acktun, Andreas: air traffic in Germany and the United Kingdom in 1924 to 1946, Marburg 2006, Apparently, a significant number of aircraft was destroyed after the cease-fire, since the air force on 29. In February 1944, had only 15 planes (one of the DLH). At least four aircraft had been delivered up to this time, from the new manufacture.On the instructions of the German troops, the production of the G. 12 delivery in Turin, until she was stopped in August 1944. Within this period, the W. no. 53 to 70 were built. The air force took over, however, only 12 aircraft to 30. June, 1944, and another in July/August,BA/MA Freiburg, stock RL 3, manufacturing programs, so that it is likely that five aircraft were destroyed by bombing.The construction was carried out, since the air force with the G. 12, the air transport squadron 4, the before, the Savoia-Marchetti SM.82 flew, gave. In December 1943, the first eight aircraft were delivered. The maximum stock level amounted to 22 aircraft on the 30. April 1944. The season, however, was used only a little, and suffered a total of five losses, including only two by enemy action. In September 1944, the last of the 18 aircraft were sold to the Hungarian air force. The last Hungarian G. 12 were then on the 22. In March 1945 destroyed.Kössler, Karl: The aircraft, the Fiat G 12, in the services of the air force, in aircraft, 2/87, p. 12-14The Italian post-war air force, the G. 12 is a set up in the 1950s and took over 1948/49 including the last four aircraft being built (to W. Nr. 101-104).
Civil VerwendungDie Aviolinee received in November 1941, W. no. 7 I-ALIC, in March 1942, the W. no. 9 I-ALID and in April 1942, W. no. 13 I-ALIG, and put them on their civilian routes to Eastern Europe. In June and July 1943, the company received two new aircraft: W. Nr. 44 I-ALIR and W. no. 46 I-ALI.The airline LATI showed up in 1941, is also interested in the aircraft, to the South Atlantic, the previously used Savoia-Marchetti SM track.82 and SM.83 replace can. The G. 12 offered the advantage that you can fly in an altitude of 6,500 to 7,000 m, and thus a large part of the weather under. She was also devices, in contrast to the other two all-metal aircraft with Autopilot and efficient de-Icing. After the LATI on the 19. December 1941 had to adjust your South America traffic, she received, in may 1942, the W. no. 14 I FOLLOW, and in July 1942, two more aircraft of this type: W. no. 17 I-FAUN and W. no. 18 I-FELI. The aircraft were mainly used on the route Rome–Sevilia–Lisbon, until they were recalled in November 1942, for the supply of Italian troops in Tunisia. The I-FELI on a flight from Tobruk to Athens to Crete from lack of fuel going down had to where the plane was lost. The two remaining aircraft had to be on 2. In February 1943, assigned to the 48° Stormo Trasporti of the SAS.In 1942 the development of a G. 12 was launched with a very large range. She was as an Alternative to the Savoia-Marchetti SM.75 for the flight Rome-Tokyo, provided, however, came not as a result of the SM.75 preferred. Two versions were built: the G. 12 RT, with an 8,000 km range, and the G. 12 RT, up to 9,000 km range.In 1942, the Hungarian MALERT for the G. 12 in the civil execution interested, after you had had to hand in their Junkers Ju 52/3m to the Hungarian air force. You ordered a total of 14 G. 12. 15. September of 1942 was delivered to the first plane, until the Italian armistice of five more followed still (W.-Nr. 25, 35, 36, 43, 48, 51). However, it is assumed that this aircraft flew also not of the MALERT, but in the case of the Hungarian air force since no civilian approvals for these airplanes.In 1947, the Aviolinee the following aircraft in the inventory: W no.40 I-VIDA, W. no. 72 I-VIDI, W. no. 71 I-VIDO.In the same year, the Alitalia flew the W. no. 81 I-DALI, W. no. 83 I-DALF, W. no. 84 I-DALG and W. no. 86 I-DALH, all of which were equipped with 18 passenger seats. By the end of 1947 to 1948, the Alitalia received a further five aircraft: W. Nr. 95-99, I-DALA to I-DALE. In 1950, the aircraft were withdrawn from circulation.The article is based on: Brotzu, E./Cosolo, G.: Dimensione Cielo No. 9: Trasporto, Roma 1976, p. 37-56
